December 29, 2023 â€“ The Year 2023 In Review!

As we close out 2023, I want to take a little time to reflect on an amazing year filled with touring, great performances with great musicians, great friendships, personal and musical growth, the sad loss of two close blues musician friends, five CD releases, amazing press and recognition, lots of airplay, a few feature articles, a bunch of award nominations, and a handful of wins!

Thank you all my friends and fans, my record label VizzTone Label Group, my publicist Amy Brat/BratGirlMedia, my behind-the-scenes production heroes Clarke Rigsby, John, Wroble, Kid, Anderson, Vince Ray, Jimi Giannatti, and Jeff Taylor, the great staff at the Rhythm Room, headed by manager Lynsey Curtis, and all of my amazing fans from all around the world who show me so much love and support! I count my blessings every day. So letâ€™s review some of the highlights of the year.

Album Releases!

This year I was able to release five powerful albums!

Awards!

This year I received lots of nominations and a handful of wins!

Feature Articles!

Here are just a few of the articles from 2023, but for a complete list of all articles, click here.

A Year Filled With Live Performances!

2023 saw so many fantastic stages in both North America and Europe! There were seven out of the country trips, and lots of USA festivals and special shows. Of course my homebase in Phoenix is the Rhythm Room and there were a lot of great nights over there! Here is a complete list of 2023 scheduled performances:

Passings

Itâ€™s always sad to see your close associates pass away, but I feel blessed and enriched to have known both Bill Howl-N-Madd Perry and Tail Dragger. Iâ€™m very proud to have made music with them and shared many smiles. Tail Dragger was a lifelong friend who I met in 1976 at a memorial tribute to Howlinâ€™ Wolf. I met Bill Perry much later, but our friendship and bond was immediate. I cherished both of these friendships with my whole heart. They are missed.

The Amazing Successes And Achievements Of My Close Collaborators!

I feel blessed to have such a close nit group of friends that have had so much success.

John Primer â€“ The legendary John Primer had a spectacular year. Check out his list of achievements:

Jimi Primetime Smith â€“ Primetime moved to Phoenix seven years ago and we partnered up immediately. It seem like the collective momentum really hit this year. With Jimi getting two high profile cover stories, and our collaboration album World In A Jug got lots of airplay on XM and lots of positive attention accross the board. Be on the lookout for this rising Bluesman, as more and more people become aware of his great talent!

Bob Stroger â€“ having just turned 93 years young on December 27, Bob Stroger is the greatest Chicago blues bassist alive and heâ€™s finally beginning to get some of his long overdue recognition! This is a great year for Mr. Stroger and we believe thereâ€™s much more to come!

Bob Margolin â€“ It was great to see him get a Blues Blast Magazine Lifetime Achievement Award. Bob Margolin works tirelessly for The Blues and participates actively in the Pinetop Perkins Foundation, educating the youth about The Blues! He also has been very active in the Last Waltz tours. He plays with many musicians and I always love when we get the opportunity to work together. Bob Margolin is also a partner in VizzTone Label Group!

Bobby Rush, Johnny Rawls, Oscar Wilson, Ben Levin, Anthony Geraci, Tornetta Davis, Willie Buck, Lurrie Bell, Tia Carroll, Alabama Mike, Diunna Greenleaf â€“ These great blues musicians are very active and have been receiving lots of high profile recognition!

A Great Year For Spotify!

In Summary

There are so many photos and posters from this amazing year, and there would be no way I could fit them all into an email. But I do plan on creating a photo page with highlights from 2023. When that is completed, I will let you know via this newsletter.

I am so grateful for this year. I donâ€™t think that I have ever had a year this active before. I feel that I have continued to improve my Harmonica craft and Iâ€™m doing my best playing ever right now. I hope to continue to grow and learn on my instrument and be able to advance my musical expression and showmanship. Somehow the world has allowed me this wonderful life path which Iâ€™m thoroughly enjoying. I am so grateful for all my wonderful fans who show me so much love and appreciation. Wishing everybody a fantastic 2024 filled with all of your dreams realized! I thank you with all my heart.

Some Parting Shots!

December 27, 2023 â€“ Today Is Bob Strogerâ€˜s 93rd Birthday!

Happy 93rd birthday to Bob Stroger. Born Dec 27, 1930, Bob Stroger has had over seven decades, playing music professionally! This legendary, Bass Player is still touring the world, and is playing at the top of his game. And on top of that, in the last decade heâ€™s really developed as a front man and singer, charming audiences all around the world and releasing critically acclaimed albums. Bob Stoger literally has worked with every Chicago blues legend imaginable, and to this day is still the Bass Player of choice for all traditionalists. And on top of all of this, heâ€™s one of the kindest, happiest, best dressed musicians on the planet. So today letâ€™s honor this great man on his birthday! Much love to Bob Stroger!

VIZZTONE LABEL GROUP TO RELEASE NEW BOB CORRITORE & FRIENDS ALBUM, â€œPHOENIX BLUES RUMBLEâ€, DECEMBER 1, 2023

BOSTON, MA â€“ VizzTone is proud to announce the September 29 release of PHOENIX BLUES RUMBLE, Bob Corritoreâ€™slatest â€œFrom The Vaultsâ€ album culled from his vast archives.

PHOENIX BLUES RUMBLE is a showcase of the artists from Bob Corritoreâ€™s adopted home town of Phoenix, Arizona. Recorded between 1987 and 2017, itâ€™s a peek into a Southwest US community that has spawned a powerful blues scene.

Blues harp player Bob Corritore moved from Chicago to Phoenix in 1981, and it quickly became a Blues hub. Bob played with local bluesmen Tommy Dukes, Chief Schabuttie Gilliame, Big Pete Pearson and Dino Spells, and persuaded his Chicago friend Chico Chism to move to town. Corritore started his long-running radio show, â€œThose Lowdown Bluesâ€ on KJZZ in 1984 â€“ Itâ€™s about to celebrate its 49th Anniversary â€“ and he opened the Rhythm Room music club and started bringing blues artists to Phoenix for performances and recording sessions. Those many sessions were to become the fertile ground for his â€œFrom the Vaultsâ€ album series. Before long Sugaray Rayfordmoved nearby. Behold the power of Phoenix Blues!

The first single features Hattiesburg, MS native Tommy Dukes, who relocated to Arizona in the mid-1950s and has been a prominent blues force in the area ever since. Bob Corritore met Tommy the first week he arrived in Phoenix in 1981, and over the years theyâ€™ve maintained a great friendship and worked numerous shows together. Tommy reactivates his childhood blues inspiration by playing in the Jimmy Reed style on his original composition, â€œReal Bad Day.â€ Tommyâ€™s relaxed vocals and groovinâ€™ guitar provide the foil for Corritoreâ€™s straight-ahead harmonica playing on this real deal blues.

Bob Corritoreâ€™s latest masterpiece collection of newly recorded songs featuring a spectacular offering of top blues artists on the scene today. Bobâ€™s brilliant harmonica work is the connecting thread, effortlessly tying together a great variety of blues styles and always serving the song.

Unlike Corritoreâ€™s â€œFrom the Vaultsâ€ series albums, these are all freshly recorded tracks, and they reflect the diverse richness of todayâ€™s blues world. Guest vocalists shine, and Corritoreâ€™s production touch brings out different and extra cool aspects of each artistâ€™s performance. Listening to this album is like going to an awesome blues festival filled with one heartfelt performance after another.

The first single, â€œGood As It Getsâ€ features blues icon and Grammy winner Bobby Rush. Co-produced by Bob Corritore and Clarke Rigsby, the lineup includes drum legend Steve Ferrone, organist Chester Thompson, and guitarists Dexter Allen and Jimi â€œPrimetimeâ€ Smith, delivering a powerful and funky groove for vocalist Rush to work with. Harmonica ace Corritore sparsely teases his way around the vocals until itâ€™s time to explode for the solo.

The amazing list of featured vocalists includes Bobby Rush, Thornetta Davis, John Primer, Carl Weathersby, Johnny Rawls, Eugene â€œHideawayâ€ Bridges, Francine Reed, Tia Carroll, Oscar Wilson, Diunna Greenleaf, Jimi â€œPrimetimeâ€ Smith, Willie Buck, Sugaray Rayford, and Lurrie Bell. In addition to the vocalists, this album features some of todayâ€™s best blues intrumentalists, including Bob Margolin, Bob Stroger, Anthony Geraci, Ben Levin, Johnny Burgin, Kid Ramos, Billy Flynn, Bill Stuve, Fred Kaplan, Dave Keyes, Doug James, Johnny Main, Johny Rapp, Yahni Riley, Kedar Roy, Troy Sandow, Mike King, Brian Fahey, June Core, Steven Hodges, Wes Starr and more.

RIP Tail Dragger. September 30, 1940 â€“ September 4, 2023.

Itâ€™s hard to say goodbye to somebody who has been a constant presence in the Chicago blue scene for many decades. James Yancey Jones, also known as Tail Dragger performed his heavy duty, Howlinâ€™ Wolf inspired blues around Chicago and around the world since the 1970s. His band was also a training ground for so many aspiring artists who came to know the real Blues by playing with this master. He was a fun-loving, rowdy-making character with a rough exterior, an outspoken persona, a kind and loyal friend, and a street-wise teacher. Bob Corritore first met Tail Dragger in 1976, the day after Howlinâ€™ Wolf died. All of the musicians that loved Howlinâ€™ Wolf gathered at the club that Wolf used to play at on the West Side â€“ Eddie Shawâ€™s 1815 club. Bob Corritore did not realize at that moment that this larger than life character would become a lifelong friend and they made recordings together, toured all over the world and shared many smiles. This was not an exclusive situation in any way, because Tail Dragger made friends and musical associates wherever he went. But when you were in with Tail Dragger, you became part of his entrusted team. Here are a selection of photos from Bobâ€™s collection of some really great times had. He will be greatly missed and there is nobody that could possibly ever replace him.
